         <abstract>
            <p>A factoring method is presented which, heuristically, splits composite n in O(n&lt;sup&gt;1/4+ε&lt;/sup&gt;) steps. There are two ideas: an integer approximation to √(q/p) provides an O(n&lt;sup&gt;1/2+ε&lt;/sup&gt;) algorithm in which n is represented as the difference of two rational squares; observing that if a prime m divides a square, then m&lt;sup&gt;2&lt;/sup&gt; divides that square, a heuristic speed-up to O(n&lt;sup&gt;1/4+ε&lt;/sup&gt;) steps is achieved. The method is well-suited for use with small computers: the storage required is negligible, and one never needs to work with numbers larger than n itself.</p>
          </abstract>
